<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12121c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12121c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12121c"> 121(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lavandi&egrave;res de nuit / washed on Sunday</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Non moins durement punies sont les <mark>Lavandi&egrave;res</mark> qui ont m&eacute;connu la loi de Dieu, <mark>en travaillant le dimanche</mark>. Elles sont condamn&eacute;es &agrave;tordre leur linge et &agrave;jouer du battoir &agrave;longueur <mark>de nuit</mark>. <font color="green">[...]</font> <mark>Les lavandi&egrave;res</mark> p&eacute;nitentes de Brennilis semblent accepter assez gaiement leur ch&acirc;timent: elles chantent. Par les nuits obscures, on entend leur voix monter des bords de l&apos;Ellez, et le cantique qu&apos;elles r&eacute;p&egrave;tent est si doux, si suave, si m&eacute;lodieux, qu&apos;on le croi-rait emprunt&eacute; aux choeurs des anges. <br><font color="green">[No less harshly punished are the washerwomen who disregarded the law of God, working on Sundays. They are condemned to wring their clothes and to play beating at night. [...]</font> The penitential washerwomen of Brennilis seem to accept their punishment cheerfully enough: they sing. By the dark nights we can hear their voices rising from the banks of the Ellez, and the canticle they repeat is so sweet, so sweet, so melodious, that we believe it borrowed from the choruses of the angels <small> Fran&ccedil;ois Cadic, <a name="NCEL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#NCEL"><cite title="source">Nouveaux contes et l&eacute;gendes de Bretagne</cite></a> (1922) 101</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
